      • getArgumentTypes

        public ArgumentTypes[] getArgumentTypes()
        Description copied from interface: ICommand
        Gets the argument types for the command parameters. If an argument is optional, use ArgumentTypes.optional(). If your command takes special arguments that cannot be processed by this API, then make sure to include ArgumentTypes.CUSTOM at the end of this array. If the command does not take any arguments, this method can return null.

        NOTE: ArgumentTypes.CUSTOM is not used for custom arguments. If you want your command to take a special/custom argument, then use ArgumentTypes.STRING, and parse the argument in ICommand.execute(MessageReceivedEvent, CommandRegistry, String, Object...).

        NOTICE: Array and optional types must be the last arguments in the arguments array. Each command may only have one optional argument. Command may not have both array and optional arguments.
        Specified by:
        getArgumentTypes in interface ICommand
        Returns:
        the argument types, or null.

      • execute

        public void execute(net.dv8tion.jda.core.events.message.MessageReceivedEvent event,
                    CommandRegistry registry,
                    java.lang.String prefix,
                    java.lang.Object... arguments)
        Description copied from interface: ICommand
        Executes this command. ICommand.getArgumentTypes() will be invoked on the command instance before this method is called. If it returns an array with at least one element, then the message which triggered the command will be processed into an array of objects such that each element will have the data type defined in the corresponding argument-types array, and will passed this this method upon invocation. In other words, you don't have to manually divide the message and parse the various arguments. All you to do is cast each element from the arguments array passed to this method.
        Specified by:
        execute in interface ICommand
        Parameters:
        event - the event that triggered this command. This is provided for commands that need more than just arguments to execute.
        registry - the command registry which this command is registered in. This parameter is generally used by help commands.
        prefix - The command prefix the guild which the event originated from.
        arguments - the user-provided arguments, or null.
